AB  - This document provides a structured cross-jurisdictional analysis of the legal, regulatory, contractual, and liability surface areas relevant to a personal rule-layer embedded in technology. The scope covers Germany (DE), the European Union (EU), and the United States (US), and examines interactions between individuals (as employees, contractors, citizens, and consumers), organizations (as employers, clients, platforms), and technology used for personal adaptation, assistance, decision support, or automation. The analysis enumerates applicable legal domains, typical liability and attribution pathways, and derives minimum invariant requirements that a personal rule-layer must satisfy in order to:(a) avoid attributable harm or liability for employers, organizations, or third parties, and(b) preserve the individual’s ability for free development across professional, economic, and civic ecosystems. The document is intentionally non-operational: it does not provide implementation guidance, system architecture, code, or deployment instructions. Instead, it focuses on requirements extraction, constraint identification, and risk-gating logic that can serve as a neutral upstream reference for governance, compliance, legal review, and system design. Outputs include a comprehensive domain taxonomy, per-domain requirement matrices, cross-domain invariants, identified gaps requiring contextual decisions (e.g. deployment or data models), and a completeness self-check against core regulatory areas such as employment law, data protection, cybersecurity, IP, export controls, financial regulation, platform policies, and AI-specific regulation. The document is intended for use as a reference artifact in legal analysis, policy development, governance design, and interdisciplinary research. It does not constitute legal advice.
